  "prompt": "How do I get IR with my Samsung Galaxy 7 so I can use my phone as a TV remote?",
  "response": "Unfortunately, the Samsung Galaxy S7 **does not have an IR (infrared) blaster**. This means you cannot directly use it as a universal remote for your TV or other devices that rely on infrared signals.\n\nIR blasters were a feature on some older Samsung phones, but they were discontinued.\n\n**Alternative Solutions:**\n\nWhile you can't use IR, here are some alternative ways to control your TV with your Galaxy S7:\n\n1.  **Smart TVs with Wi-Fi Control:**\n\n    *   If your TV is a \"smart\" TV with Wi-Fi connectivity, you can likely download a dedicated remote control app from the TV manufacturer (e.g., Samsung SmartThings, LG ThinQ, Sony's TV SideView, etc.)  These apps connect to your TV over your Wi-Fi network and allow you to control basic functions like power, volume, channel, and sometimes more advanced features.\n    *   **Check your TV's user manual or manufacturer's website to find the appropriate app.**\n    *   Make sure your phone and TV are on the same Wi-Fi network.\n\n2.  **Chromecast/Roku/Apple TV:**\n\n    *   If you have a streaming device like a Chromecast, Roku, or Apple TV connected to your TV, you can use the respective app on your Galaxy S7 to control the device.  This allows you to control the content being streamed, and often includes basic TV controls like volume.\n\n3.  **Google Assistant/Alexa:**\n\n    *   If you have a smart speaker like a Google Home/Nest or Amazon Echo, you can potentially control your TV through voice commands, especially if you also have a Chromecast or Fire TV Stick.  You'll need to link your accounts and devices.\n\n4.  **Bluetooth Remote Apps:**\n\n    * Some TVs use Bluetooth remotes. In that case you might be able to pair with your TV via bluetooth and control it that way. Check the TV manual for instructions.\n\n**In summary, the Galaxy S7 lacks the built-in IR blaster necessary to function as a traditional universal remote.  You'll need to explore Wi-Fi-based apps, streaming device control, or voice assistant integration as alternatives.**\n",
